How do game engines work , as in , why are some used more frequently than others ? Also , how do they make money , and why is that I can usually tell if a game is made with , say , the Havoc 3 engine ? Explain like I'm five.
model
Okay, so, imagine you're building a really cool Lego castle, right? You need instructions to make sure all the pieces fit together. Well, a game engine is like a super-detailed set of instructions for making video games. Instead of Lego blocks, it's instructions for all the things that need to happen in the game, like moving characters, making explosions, and playing music.

Now, some of these instructions are really good and easy to use, and some are more complicated and hard to use, so the more complicated ones are usually not used much.

But, how do they make money? Well, most of the game engines are free, and the people who make them are paid by the people who use them. So, if a game company wants to make a game, they'll pay the game engine company to make them an engine to use.

Also, some game companies will pay for a game engine to make them a game.

response:
user
How does NAT ( Network Address Translation ) work . I 've googled it and all the answers are very complex . I need it explained to me like I 'm five . Thanks ! Explain like I'm five.
model
Okay, so imagine you have a bunch of friends who want to send each other letters. But each friend only has one address, and there's not enough room for everyone. So, we have a post office that can help. The post office takes all the letters from your friends, and writes a new address on each one that says, "From: [Friend's Name], To: [Your Name]" and then sends it to you. When you send a letter to a friend, you write the friend's original address, but the post office changes it to "From: [Your Name], To: [Friend's Name]" before sending it. That's basically how NAT works. The computer is like the post office, and the public network is like the outside world.
